    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid is formed during anaerobic respiration when the body breaks down glucose without oxygen, typically during intense exercise where the demand for energy surpasses the oxygen supply. This process, known as the lactic acid fermentation, occurs within the muscles and converts glucose into lactic acid and energy. The body then clears out lactic acid through the Cori cycle, which transports it to the liver and converts it back into glucose that can be used for energy, and through metabolism in other tissues like the heart and brain. During recovery, aerobic respiration restores normal oxygen levels in the muscles, allowing lactic acid to be further processed and removed from the body.",
      "source": "target",
